<subSubSection id="08FB941E647FDE9973228E329C75E237" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" type="description">
<paragraph id="2F761A73346A7A8D01DE1BD811BD2D4D" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A9B66FB0BF1A569E890593AEF855D6EE" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
The collected specimens match with the descriptions of 
<bibRefCitation id="2A33A6BB5B7023C87025B38659AD7743" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1515/botm.1991.34.2.153" author="Verlaque, M" journalOrPublisher="Botanica Marina" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="153 - 160" refId="B65" refString="Verlaque, M, Seridi, H, 1991. Antithamnion algeriensis nov. sp. (Ceramiaceae, Rhodophyta) from Algeria (Mediterranean Sea). Botanica Marina 34: 153 - 160, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1515/botm.1991.34.2.153" title="Antithamnion algeriensis nov. sp. (Ceramiaceae, Rhodophyta) from Algeria (Mediterranean Sea)." url="https://doi.org/10.1515/botm.1991.34.2.153" volume="34" year="1991">Verlaque and Seridi (1991)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EEAAD186820AD5B7BCAE88FE89CB3286" author="Cormaci, M" journalOrPublisher="Recent Research Developments in Environmental Biology" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="153 - 202" refId="B16" refString="Cormaci, M, Furnari, G, Giaccone, G, Serio, D, 2004. Alien macrophytes in the Mediterranean Sea: a review. Recent Research Developments in Environmental Biology 1: 153 - 202" title="Alien macrophytes in the Mediterranean Sea: a review." volume="1" year="2004">Cormaci et al. (2004)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="565CB37D7A42E07AF00CEBD3F2D80145" author="Rodriguez-Prieto, C" journalOrPublisher="Ediciones Omega, Barcelona" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" refId="B52" refString="Rodriguez-Prieto, C, Ballesteros, E, Boisset, F, Afonso-Carrillo, J, 2013. Guia de las Macroalgas y Fanerogamas Marinas del Mediterraneo Occidental. Ediciones Omega, Barcelona" title="Guia de las Macroalgas y Fanerogamas Marinas del Mediterraneo Occidental." year="2013">
<normalizedToken id="6B405780B206430EAA5D905DF65D63CE" originalValue="Rodríguez-Prieto">Rodriguez-Prieto</normalizedToken>
et al. (2013)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="0395598DEDE4F7A544630420443831B9" author="Verlaque, M" journalOrPublisher="CIESM Publishers, Monaco" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" refId="B67" refString="Verlaque, M, Ruitton, S, Mineur, F, Boudouresque, CF, 2015. CIESM Atlas of Exotic Species in the Mediterranean, Vol. 4 Macrophytes. CIESM Publishers, Monaco" title="CIESM Atlas of Exotic Species in the Mediterranean, Vol. 4 Macrophytes." year="2015">Verlaque et al. (2015)</bibRefCitation>
. The thalli are pink-reddish, filamentous and uniseriate, consisting of creeping and erect axes, bearing distichous opposite whorl branches. The whorl branches have an isodiametric basal cell and bear opposite distichous simple or branched branchlets with only abaxial branchlets near the distal portion. As reported by 
<bibRefCitation id="6443DC40C0DF827CCEF1BD99D27AD341" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1515/botm.1997.40.1-6.329" author="Secilla, A" journalOrPublisher="Botanica Marina" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="329 - 332" refId="B59" refString="Secilla, A, Gorostiaga, JM, Diez, I, Santolaria, A, 1997. Antithamnion amphigeneum (Ceramiales, Rhodophyta) from the European Atlantic coast. Botanica Marina 40: 329 - 332, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1515/botm.1997.40.1-6.329" title="Antithamnion amphigeneum (Ceramiales, Rhodophyta) from the European Atlantic coast." url="https://doi.org/10.1515/botm.1997.40.1-6.329" volume="40" year="1997">Secilla et al. (1997)</bibRefCitation>
, we noticed in our samples that the apical cells are blunt and sometimes provided with a single hyaline hair (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="65C3F3894C2D2DC53B3460049B900670" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Antithamnion amphigeneum a apical portion of an indefinite axes: the arrowhead shows a terminal hyaline hair b detail of lateral indeterminate branches, which arise by replacing a branchlet and with the suppression of the opposite branchlet (arrow)." figureDoi="10.3897/italianbotanist.11.60474.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/523937" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">2A</figureCitation>
). The lateral indeterminate branches arise replacing a branchlet and with the suppression of the opposite branchlet (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="C8228F2DE5B0A14B464F848391225D35" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Antithamnion amphigeneum a apical portion of an indefinite axes: the arrowhead shows a terminal hyaline hair b detail of lateral indeterminate branches, which arise by replacing a branchlet and with the suppression of the opposite branchlet (arrow)." figureDoi="10.3897/italianbotanist.11.60474.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/523937" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">2B</figureCitation>
). Moreover, in the collected specimens there were abundant gland cells located on the adaxial side of both normal and special branchlets, touching 2-3 cells. We found only sterile specimens.
</paragraph>
<caption id="C209E9488E53691CCDC4DDF431C2CDF7" doi="10.3897/italianbotanist.11.60474.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/523937" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" start="Figure 2" startId="F2">
<paragraph id="FD755A0070DD6443DE63467680FA8FFE" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis id="A28E5D0EE2C68E582648C93E109FD7AD" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Figure 2.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="6582D2362BE2069FA3B93F72818D0EA1" class="Florideophyceae" family="Ceramiaceae" genus="Antithamnion" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Antithamnion amphigeneum" order="Ceramiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Rhodophyta" rank="species" species="amphigeneum">
<emphasis id="75856126D7DD9F8C3517499A1A6BE4C9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Antithamnion amphigeneum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="0D7951AE6C47A8CD378FB93E43954137" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">a</emphasis>
apical portion of an indefinite axes: the arrowhead shows a terminal hyaline hair 
<emphasis id="BD2C2957BC4907B915283246A09E7AC5" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">b</emphasis>
detail of lateral indeterminate branches, which arise by replacing a branchlet and with the suppression of the opposite branchlet (arrow).
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
